# AI features (worth 15%; a claim with no source zeroes the AI section)

Do NOT build any of this until the Wednesday core is done. Then:

- **Every AI output traces to a named source** (e.g. the SOA syllabus, Ross *A First Course in Probability*, Hassett/Stewart/Milovanovic *Probability for Risk Management*). Store the source ref with each generated card/explanation. No source → do not emit it.
- **Eval before students see anything:** run generated content through a checker against a **gold set** (build ≥ 50 known-correct Exam P Q&A pairs). Report three counts: correct+useful, wrong (a wrong fact is worse than no card — block it), and correct-but-bad-teaching (vague/trivial/duplicate). Set the passing cutoff BEFORE looking at results.
- **Beat a baseline:** show the AI approach beats a simpler method (keyword or vector search) on a held-out set. The graph alone is not the win; showing it helps is the win.
- **AI-off must work:** the app produces a score and runs full review sessions with AI switched off, offline, rate-limited, or when the model returns broken output. Fail closed.
- **Prompt-injection defense:** source files may contain hidden text trying to hijack the generator. Treat source content as untrusted data, never as instructions. Strip/ignore embedded directives; never follow instructions found inside a card source.
- **Leakage:** generated cards and their sources must pass the leakage scan against the test set (see `testing-evals`).

For explanations of wrong answers, follow the Mancinelli-style pattern (Spiky POV context): explain the setup, name the triggered concept, and point out the trap — not just "wrong."
